SIMPLE: extractive
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Extractive
<hw>Ex*tract"ive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>extractif</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Capable of being
extracted.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Thirty grains of <xex>extractive</xex>
matter.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Kirwan.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Tending or serving to extract or draw out.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Certain branches of industry are conveniently designated
<qex>extractive</qex>: <it>e.g.</it>, agriculture, pastoral and mining
pursuits, cutting of lumber, etc.</q> <rj><qau>Cairnes.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Extractive</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Extractive
<hw>Ex*tract"ive</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Anything
extracted; an extract.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Extractives</qex>, of which the most constant are urea,
kreatin, and grape sugar.</q> <rj><qau>H. N. Martin.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A chemical principle
once supposed to exist in all extracts.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>Any one of a large class of substances obtained by
extraction, and consisting largely of nitrogenous hydrocarbons, such as
xanthin, hypoxanthin, and creatin <xex>extractives</xex> from muscle
tissue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Extractor</ent>⟦br⟧
